{"formatVersion":"1","manifest":{"primaryCategory":"Faith & Devotion","subcategory":"Sufism","audienceTags":["tradition:sufism","theme:wisdom","theme:self-knowledge","audience:meditation"],"sortPriority":31,"groupingLevels":[],"groupingLabels":[],"dataPath":"Data/Collections/Attar_Birds.json","supplementalDataPath":null,"languageCode":"en","displayNameEnglish":"Attar — Conference of Birds","script":"Latin","isRTL":false,"transliterationAvailable":false,"contentRating":"devotional","sourceId":"attarBirds","displayName":"Attar — Conference of Birds","version":"1.0","language":"English","edition":"FitzGerald Translation","type":"quotes","browseOrder":"sequence","itemCount":417,"supportsRandom":true,"supportsBrowse":true},"data":[{"id":"attar-ext-000001","text":"I shall grasp the soul's skirt with my hand and stamp on the world's head with my foot. I shall trample Matter and Space with my horse,beyond all Being I shall utter a great shout,and in that moment when I shall be alone with Him, I shall whisper secrets to all mankind. Since I have neither sign nor name I shall speak only of things unnamed and without sign.","author":"Attar","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000002","text":"The SeaWill be the SeaWhatever the drop's philosophy.","author":"Attar","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000003","text":"Your face is neither infinite nor ephemeral.You can never see your own face,only a reflection, not the face itself.","author":"Attar","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000004","text":"Don't be dead or asleep or awake.Don't be anything.What you most want,what you travel around wishing to find,lose yourself as lovers lose themselves,and you'll be that.","author":"Attar","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000005","text":"Joy! Joy! I triumph! Now no more I knowMyself as simply me. I burn with loveUnto myself, and bury me in love.The centre is within me and its wonderLies as a circle everywhere about me.Joy! Joy! No mortal thought can fathom me.","author":"Attar","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:love","theme:mortality","theme:self-knowledge","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000006","text":"From each a mystic silence Love demands.What do all seek so earnestly? 'Tis Love.What do they whisper to each other? Love.Love is the subject of their inmost thoughts.In Love no longer \"thou\" and \"I\" exist,For Self has passed away in the Beloved.","author":"Attar","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000007","text":"He who would know the secret of both worlds,Will find the secret of them both, is Love.","author":"Attar","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000008","text":"Do all you can to become a bird of the Way to God;Do all you can to develop your wings and your feathers.","author":"Attar","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000009","text":"Yet what are seas and what is air? For allIs God, and but a talisman are heaven and earthTo veil Divinity. For heaven and earth,Did He not permeate them, were but names;Know then, that both this visible world and thatWhich unseen is, alike are God Himself,Naught is, save God: and all that is, is God.","author":"Attar","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000010","text":"Thou all Creation art, all we behold, but Thou,The soul within the body lies concealed,And Thou dost hide Thyself within the soul,O soul in soul! Myst'ry in myst'ry hid!Before all wert Thou, and are more than all!","author":"Attar","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000011","text":"All things are but masks at God's beck and call,They are symbols that instruct us that God is all.","author":"Attar","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000012","text":"All you have been, and seen, and done, and thought,Not You but I, have seen and been and wrought:I was the Sin that from Myself rebell'd:I the Remorse that tow'rd Myself compell'd...","author":"Attar","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000013","text":"Sin and Contrition — Retribution owed,And cancell'd — Pilgrim, Pilgrimage, and Road,Was but Myself toward Myself: and YourArrival but Myself at my own Door...","author":"Attar","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000014","text":"Come you lost Atoms to your Centre draw,And be the Eternal Mirror that you saw:Rays that have wander'd into Darkness wideReturn and back into your Sun subside.","author":"Attar","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000015","text":"My friends, a shower of roses from that gardenAs my memoir upon your heads I've rained down.Since everyone has made some kind of contribution,Set forth another revelation and passed on,So I as well like all the rest have shownThe sleepers how the bird of the soul has flown.","author":"Attar","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000016","text":"Attar has roamed through the seven cities of love while we have barely turned down the first street.","author":"Attar","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000017","text":"\"Farid al-Din 'Attar\" by Iraj Bashiri","author":"Attar","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000018","text":"Produced by Jonathan Ingram, Sandra Brown and the DP Team","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000019","text":"A STORY OF THE INNER VISION OF THE HIGHLANDERS,","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000020","text":"Allow me, with the honour due to my father’s friend, to inscribe this little volume with your name. The name of one friend is better than those of all the Muses.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000021","text":"And permit me to say a few words about the story.--It is a Romance.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000022","text":"I am well aware that, with many readers, this epithet will be enough to ensure condemnation.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000023","text":"But there ought to be a place for any story, which, although founded in the marvellous, is true to human nature and to itself.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000024","text":"Truth to Humanity, and harmony within itself, are almost the sole unvarying essentials of a work of art.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:solitude","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000025","text":"Even _The Rime of the Ancient Mariner_--than which what more marvellous?--is true in these respects.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000026","text":"And Shakespere himself will allow any amount of the marvellous, provided this truth is observed.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000027","text":"I hope my story is thus true; and therefore, while it claims some place, undeserving of being classed with what are commonly called _sensational novels._","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000028","text":"I am well aware that such tales are not of much account, at present; and greatly would I regret that they should ever become the fashion; of which, however, there is no danger.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000029","text":"If I confined my pen to such results, you, at least, would have a right to blame me.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000030","text":"But you, for one, will, I am sure, justify an author in dreaming _sometimes_.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000031","text":"In offering you a story, however, founded on _The Second Sight_, the belief in which was common to our ancestors, I owe you, at the same time, an apology.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000032","text":"For the tone and colour of the story are so different from those naturally belonging to a Celtic tale, that you might well be inclined to refuse my request, simply on the ground that your pure Highland blood revolted from the degenerate embodiment given to the ancient belief.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000033","text":"I can only say that my early education was not Celtic enough to enable me to do better in this respect.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000034","text":"I beg that you will accept the offering with forgiveness, if you cannot with approbation.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000035","text":"_To_ DUNCAN MCCOLL, Esq., R.N., _Huntly._","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000036","text":"My father belonged to the widespread family of the Campbells, and possessed a small landed property in the north of Argyll.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:relationships","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000037","text":"But although of long descent and high connection, he was no richer than many a farmer of a few hundred acres.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000038","text":"For, with the exception of a narrow belt of arable land at its foot, a bare hill formed almost the whole of his possessions.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000039","text":"The sheep ate over it, and no doubt found it good; I bounded and climbed all over it, and thought it a kingdom.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000040","text":"From my very childhood, I had rejoiced in being alone.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000041","text":"The sense of room about me had been one of my greatest delights.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000042","text":"Most of all, I loved it in the still autumn morning, outstretched in stillness, high uplifted towards the heaven.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000043","text":"On every stalk hung the dew in tiny drops, which, while the rising sun was low, sparkled and burned with the hues of all the gems.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000044","text":"Here and there a bird gave a cry; no other sound awoke the silence.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000045","text":"There was one spot upon the hill, half-way between the valley and the moorland, which was my favourite haunt.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000046","text":"This part of the hill was covered with great blocks of stone, of all shapes and sizes--here crowded together, like the slain where the battle had been fiercest; there parting asunder from spaces of delicate green--of softest grass.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000047","text":"This was my refuge, my home within a home, my study--and, in the hot noons, often my sleeping chamber, and my house of dreams.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000048","text":"Here I would often lie, as the sun went down, and watch the silent growth of another sea, which the stormy ocean of the wind could not disturb--the sea of the darkness.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000049","text":"First it would begin to gather in the bottom of hollow places.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000050","text":"I would lie till nothing but the stars and the dim outlines of hills against the sky was to be seen, and then rise and go home, as sure of my path as if I had been descending a dark staircase in my father’s house.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000051","text":"On the opposite side the valley, another hill lay parallel to mine; and behind it, at some miles’ distance, a great mountain.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000052","text":"As often as, in my hermit’s cave, I lifted my eyes from the volume I was reading, I saw this mountain before me.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000053","text":"Very different was its character from that of the hill on which I was seated.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000054","text":"Fearful stories were told of the gulfs, sullen waters, and dizzy heights upon that terror-haunted mountain.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000055","text":"In storms the wind roared like thunder in its caverns and along the jagged sides of its cliffs, but at other times that uplifted land-uplifted, yet secret and full of dismay--lay silent as a cloud on the horizon.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000056","text":"I had a certain peculiarity of constitution, which I have some reason to believe I inherit.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000057","text":"It seems to have its root in an unusual delicacy of hearing, which often conveys to me sounds inaudible to those about me.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000058","text":"This I have had many opportunities of proving.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000059","text":"It has likewise, however, brought me sounds which I could never trace back to their origin; though they may have arisen from some natural operation which I had not perseverance or mental acuteness sufficient to discover.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000060","text":"From this, or, it may be, from some deeper cause with which this is connected, arose a certain kind of fearfulness associated with the sense of hearing, of which I have never heard a corresponding instance.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000061","text":"When alone in bed, I used to lie awake, and look out into the room, peopling it with the forms of all the persons who had died within the scope of my memory and acquaintance.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000062","text":"These fancied forms were vividly present to my imagination.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000063","text":"I pictured them pale, with dark circles around their hollow eyes, visible by a light which glimmered within them; not the light of life, but a pale, greenish phosphorescence, generated by the decay of the brain inside.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000064","text":"Their garments were white and trailing, but torn and soiled, as by trying often in vain to get up out of the buried coffin.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000065","text":"If inadvertently I removed one of my fingers, the agony of terror I instantly experienced is indescribable.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000066","text":"I can compare it to nothing but the rushing in upon my brain of a whole churchyard of spectres.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000067","text":"The very possibility of hearing a sound, in such a mood, and at such a time, was almost enough to paralyse me.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000068","text":"So I could scare myself in broad daylight, on the open hillside, by imagining unintelligible sounds; and my imagination was both original and fertile in the invention of such.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000069","text":"But my mind was too active to be often subjected to such influences.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000070","text":"Indeed life would have been hardly endurable had these moods been of more than occasional occurrence.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000071","text":"One summer evening, I had lingered longer than usual in my rocky retreat: I had lain half dreaming in the mouth of my cave, till the shadows of evening had fallen, and the gloaming had deepened half-way towards the night.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000072","text":"But the night had no more terrors for me than the day.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000073","text":"Indeed, in such regions there is a solitariness for which there seems a peculiar sense, and upon which the shadows of night sink with a strange relief, hiding from the eye the wide space which yet they throw more open to the imagination.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000074","text":"When I lifted my head, only a star here and there caught my eye; but, looking intently into the depths of blue-grey, I saw that they were crowded with twinkles.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000075","text":"The mountain rose before me, a huge mass of gloom; but its several peaks stood out against the sky with a clear, pure, sharp outline, and looked nearer to me than the bulk from which they rose heaven-wards.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000076","text":"One star trembled and throbbed upon the very tip of the loftiest, the central peak, which seemed the spire of a mighty temple where the light was worshipped--crowned, therefore, in the darkness, with the emblem of the day.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000077","text":"I was lying, as I have said, with this fancy still in my thought, when suddenly I heard, clear, though faint and far away, the sound as of the iron-shod hoofs of a horse, in furious gallop along an uneven rocky surface.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000078","text":"It was more like a distant echo than an original sound.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000079","text":"It seemed to come from the face of the mountain, where no horse, I knew, could go at that speed, even if its rider courted certain destruction.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000080","text":"There was a peculiarity, too, in the sound--a certain tinkle, or clank, which I fancied myself able, by auricular analysis, to distinguish from the body of the sound.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000081","text":"Supposing the sound to be caused by the feet of a horse, the peculiarity was just such as would result from one of the shoes being loose.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000082","text":"A terror--strange even to my experience--seized me, and I hastened home.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000083","text":"The sounds gradually died away as I descended the hill.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000084","text":"Could they have been an echo from some precipice of the mountain?","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000085","text":"I knew of no road lying so that, if a horse were galloping upon it, the sounds would be reflected from the mountain to me.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000086","text":"The next day, in one of my rambles, I found myself near the cottage of my old foster-mother, who was distantly related to us, and was a trusted servant in the family at the time I was born.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","theme:relationships","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000087","text":"On the death of my mother, which took place almost immediately after my birth, she had taken the entire charge of me, and had brought me up, though with difficulty; for she used to tell me, I should never be either _folk_ or _fairy_.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:justice","theme:love","theme:mortality","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000088","text":"For some years she had lived alone in a cottage, at the bottom of a deep green circular hollow, upon which, in walking over a healthy table-land, one came with a sudden surprise.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:mental-health","theme:solitude","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000089","text":"She was a tall, thin, aged woman, with eager eyes, and well-defined clear-cut features.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000090","text":"Her voice was harsh, but with an undertone of great tenderness.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000091","text":"She was scrupulously careful in her attire, which was rather above her station.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000092","text":"Altogether, she had much the bearing of a gentle-woman.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000093","text":"Never having had any family of her own, although she had been the wife of one of my father’s shepherds, she expended the whole maternity of her nature upon me.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:relationships","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000094","text":"She was always my first resource in any perplexity, for I was sure of all the help she could give me.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000095","text":"And as she had much influence with my father, who was rather severe in his notions, I had had occasion to beg her interference.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000096","text":"No necessity of this sort, however, had led to my visit on the present occasion.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000097","text":"I ran down the side of the basin, and entered the little cottage.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000098","text":"Nurse was seated on a chair by the wall, with her usual knitting, a stocking, in one hand; but her hands were motionless, and her eyes wide open and fixed.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000099","text":"I knew that the neighbours stood rather in awe of her, on the ground that she had the second sight; but, although she often told us frightful enough stories, she had never alluded to such a gift as being in her possession.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000100","text":"Now I concluded at once that she was _seeing_.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000101","text":"I was confirmed in this conclusion when, seeming to come to herself suddenly, she covered her head with her plaid, and sobbed audibly, in spite of her efforts to command herself.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000102","text":"But I did not dare to ask her any questions, nor did she attempt any excuse for her behaviour.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:courage","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000103","text":"After a few moments, she unveiled herself, rose, and welcomed me with her usual kindness; then got me some refreshment, and began to question me about matters at home.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000104","text":"After a pause, she said suddenly: “When are you going to get your commission, Duncan, do you know?” I replied that I had heard nothing of it; that I did not think my father had influence or money enough to procure me one, and that I feared I should have no such good chance of distinguishing myself.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000105","text":"She did not answer, but nodded her head three times, slowly and with compressed lips--apparently as much as to say, “I know better.”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000106","text":"Just as I was leaving her, it occurred to me to mention that I had heard an odd sound the night before. She turned towards me, and looked at me fixedly. “What was it like, Duncan, my dear?”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000107","text":"“Like a horse galloping with a loose shoe,” I replied.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000108","text":"“Duncan, Duncan, my darling!” she said, in a low, trembling voice, but with passionate earnestness, “you did not hear it? Tell me that you did not hear it! You only want to frighten poor old nurse: some one has been telling you the story!”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000109","text":"It was my turn to be frightened now; for the matter became at once associated with my fears as to the possible nature of my auricular peculiarities.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000110","text":"I assured her that nothing was farther from my intention than to frighten her; that, on the contrary, she had rather alarmed me; and I begged her to explain.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000111","text":"But she sat down white and trembling, and did not speak.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000112","text":"Presently, however, she rose again, and saying, “I have known it happen sometimes without anything very bad following,” began to put away the basin and plate I had been using, as if she would compel herself to be calm before me.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000113","text":"I renewed my entreaties for an explanation, but without avail.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000114","text":"She begged me to be content for a few days, as she was quite unable to tell the story at present.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000115","text":"She promised, however, of her own accord, that before I left home she would tell me all she knew.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000116","text":"The next day a letter arrived announcing the death of a distant relation, through whose influence my father had had a lingering hope of obtaining an appointment for me. There was nothing left but to look out for a situation as tutor.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mortality","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000117","text":"A certain Lord Hilton, an English nobleman, residing in one of the midland counties, having heard that one of my father’s sons was desirous of such a situation, wrote to him, offering me the post of tutor to his two boys, of the ages of ten and twelve.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000118","text":"He had been partly educated at a Scotch university; and this, it may be, had prejudiced him in favour of a Scotch tutor; while an ancient alliance of the families by marriage was supposed by my nurse to be the reason of his offering me the situation.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000119","text":"Of this connection, however, my father said nothing to me, and it went for nothing in my anticipations.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000120","text":"I was to receive a hundred pounds a year, and to hold in the family the position of a gentleman, which might mean anything or nothing, according to the disposition of the heads of the family.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:relationships","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000121","text":"Preparations for my departure were immediately commenced.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000122","text":"I set out one evening for the cottage of my old nurse, to bid her good-bye for many months, probably years.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000123","text":"I was to leave the next day for Edinburgh, on my way to London, whence I had to repair by coach to my new abode--almost to me like the land beyond the grave, so little did I know about it, and so wide was the separation between it and my home.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000124","text":"The evening was sultry when I began my walk, and before I arrived at its end, the clouds rising from all quarters of the horizon, and especially gathering around the peaks of the mountain, betokened the near approach of a thunderstorm.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000125","text":"Gladly would I take leave of my home with the memory of a last night of tumultuous magnificence; followed, probably, by a day of weeping rain, well suited to the mood of my own heart in bidding farewell to the best of parents and the dearest of homes.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000126","text":"Besides, in common with most Scotchmen who are young and hardy enough to be unable to realise the existence of coughs and rheumatic fevers, it was a positive pleasure to me to be out in rain, hail, or snow.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000127","text":"“I am come to bid you good-bye, Margaret; and to hear the story which you promised to tell me before I left home: I go to-morrow.”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000128","text":"“Do you go so soon, my darling? Well, it will be an awful night to tell it in; but, as I promised, I suppose I must.”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000129","text":"At the moment, two or three great drops of rain, the first of the storm, fell down the wide chimney, exploding in the clear turf-fire.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000130","text":"Of course she spoke in Gaelic; and I translate from my recollection of the Gaelic; but rather from the impression left upon my mind, than from any recollection of the words.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000131","text":"She drew her chair near the fire, which we had reason to fear would soon be put out by the falling rain, and began.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000132","text":"It has come down through many generations.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000133","text":"My grandmother told it to me as I tell it to you; and her mother and my mother sat beside, never interrupting, but nodding their heads at every turn.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000134","text":"Almost it ought to begin like the fairy tales, _Once upon a time,_--it took place so long ago; but it is too dreadful and too true to tell like a fairy tale.--There were two brothers, sons of the chief of our clan, but as different in appearance and disposition as two men could be.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:justice","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000135","text":"The elder was fair-haired and strong, much given to hunting and fishing; fighting too, upon occasion, I dare say, when they made a foray upon the Saxon, to get back a mouthful of their own.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:courage","theme:justice","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000136","text":"But he was gentleness itself to every one about him, and the very soul of honour in all his doings.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000137","text":"The younger was very dark in complexion, and tall and slender compared to his brother.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000138","text":"He was very fond of book-learning, which, they say, was an uncommon taste in those times.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000139","text":"He did not care for any sports or bodily exercises but one; and that, too, was unusual in these parts.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000140","text":"He was a fierce rider, and as much at home in the saddle as in his study-chair.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000141","text":"You may think that, so long ago, there was not much fit room for riding hereabouts; but, fit or not fit, he rode.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000142","text":"From his reading and riding, the neighbours looked doubtfully upon him, and whispered about the black art.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000143","text":"He usually bestrode a great powerful black horse, without a white hair on him; and people said it was either the devil himself, or a demon-horse from the devil’s own stud.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000144","text":"What favoured this notion was, that, in or out of the stable, the brute would let no other than his master go near him.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000145","text":"Indeed, no one would venture, after he had killed two men, and grievously maimed a third, tearing him with his teeth and hoofs like a wild beast.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000146","text":"But to his master he was obedient as a hound, and would even tremble in his presence sometimes.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000147","text":"“The youth’s temper corresponded to his habits.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000148","text":"Prone to anger, he had never been known to forgive.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000149","text":"Debarred from anything on which he had set his heart, he would have gone mad with longing if he had not gone mad with rage.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000150","text":"His soul was like the night around us now, dark, and sultry, and silent, but lighted up by the red levin of wrath and torn by the bellowings of thunder-passion.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000151","text":"He must have his will: hell might have his soul.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000152","text":"Imagine, then, the rage and malice in his heart, when he suddenly became aware that an orphan girl, distantly related to them, who had lived with them for nearly two years, and whom he had loved for almost all that period, was loved by his elder brother, and loved him in return.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000153","text":"He flung his right hand above his head, swore a terrible oath that if he might not, his brother should not, rushed out of the house, and galloped off among the hills.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000154","text":"“The orphan was a beautiful girl, tall, pale, and slender, with plentiful dark hair, which, when released from the snood, rippled down below her knees.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:beauty","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000155","text":"Her appearance formed a strong contrast with that of her favoured lover, while there was some resemblance between her and the younger brother.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000156","text":"This fact seemed, to his fierce selfishness, ground for a prior claim.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000157","text":"Yet I do not suppose that he foresaw the mode in which his hatred was about to operate.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000158","text":"At the moment when he learned their mutual attachment, probably through a domestic, the lady was on her way to meet her lover as he returned from the day’s sport.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000159","text":"The appointed place was on the edge of a deep, rocky ravine, down in whose dark bosom brawled and foamed a little mountain torrent.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000160","text":"You know the place, Duncan, my dear, I dare say.”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:courage","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000161","text":"(Here she gave me a minute description of the spot, with directions how to find it.)","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000162","text":"“Whether any one saw what I am about to relate, or whether it was put together afterwards, I cannot tell.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000163","text":"The story is like an old tree--so old that it has lost the marks of its growth.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000164","text":"But this is how my grandmother told it to me.--An evil chance led him in the right direction.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000165","text":"The lovers, startled by the sound of the approaching horse, parted in opposite directions along a narrow mountain-path on the edge of the ravine.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000166","text":"Into this path he struck at a point near where the lovers had met, but to opposite sides of which they had now receded; so that he was between them on the path.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000167","text":"Turning his horse up the course of the stream, he soon came in sight of his brother on the ledge before him.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000168","text":"With a suppressed scream of rage, he rode head-long at him, and ere he had time to make the least defence, hurled him over the precipice.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000169","text":"The helplessness of the strong man was uttered in one single despairing cry as he shot into the abyss.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000170","text":"The sound of his fall could not reach the edge of the gulf.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000171","text":"Divining in a moment that the lady, whose name was Elsie, must have fled in the opposite direction, he reined his steed on his haunches.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000172","text":"He could touch the precipice with his bridle-hand half outstretched; his sword-hand half outstretched would have dropped a stone to the bottom of the ravine.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000173","text":"One desperate practicability alone remained.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000174","text":"Turning his horse’s head towards the edge, he compelled him, by means of the powerful bit, to rear till he stood almost erect; and so, his body swaying over the gulf, with quivering and straining muscles, to turn on his hind-legs.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000175","text":"Having completed the half-circle, he let him drop, and urged him furiously in the opposite direction.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000176","text":"It must have been by the devil’s own care that he was able to continue his gallop along that ledge of rock.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000177","text":"She was leaning, half fainting, against the precipice.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000178","text":"She had heard her lover’s last cry, and although it had conveyed no suggestion of his voice to her ear, she trembled from head to foot, and her limbs would bear her no farther.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000179","text":"He checked his speed, rode gently up to her, lifted her unresisting, laid her across the shoulders of his horse, and, riding carefully till he reached a more open path, dashed again wildly along the mountain-side.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000180","text":"The lady’s long hair was shaken loose, and dropped trailing on the ground.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000181","text":"The horse trampled upon it, and stumbled, half dragging her from the saddle-bow.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000182","text":"He caught her, lifted her up, and looked at her face.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000183","text":"He laid her again across the saddle before him, and rode on, reckless whither.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000184","text":"Horse, and man, and maiden were found the next day, lying at the foot of a cliff, dashed to pieces.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000185","text":"It was observed that a hind-shoe of the horse was loose and broken.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000186","text":"Whether this had been the cause of his fall, could not be told; but ever when he races, as race he will, till the day of doom, along that mountain-side, his gallop is mingled with the clank of the loose and broken shoe.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000187","text":"For, like the sin, the punishment is awful: he shall carry about for ages the phantom-body of the girl, knowing that her soul is away, sitting with the soul of his brother, down in the deep ravine, or scaling with him the topmost crags of the towering mountain-peaks.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000188","text":"There are some who, from time to time, see the doomed man careering along the face of the mountain, with the lady hanging across the steed; and they say it always betokens a storm, such as this which is now raving around us.”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000189","text":"I had not noticed till now, so absorbed had I been in her tale, that the storm had risen to a very ecstasy of fury.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000190","text":"And they say it will go on growing till the Last Day, when the horse will falter and her hair will gather in; and the horse will fall, and the hair will twist, and twine, and wreathe itself like a mist of threads about him, and blind him to everything but her.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000191","text":"Then the body will rise up within it, face to face with him, animated by a fiend, who, twining her arms around him, will drag him down to the bottomless pit.”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000192","text":"I may mention something which now occurred, and which had a strange effect on my old nurse.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000193","text":"It illustrates the assertion that we see around us only what is within us: marvellous things enough will show themselves to the marvellous mood.--During a short lull in the storm, just as she had finished her story, we heard the sound of iron-shod hoofs approaching the cottage.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000194","text":"A knock came to the door, and, on opening it, we saw an old man seated on a horse, with a long slenderly-filled sack lying across the saddle before him.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000195","text":"He said he had lost the path in the storm, and, seeing the light, had scrambled down to inquire his way.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000196","text":"I perceived at once, from the scared and mysterious look of the old woman’s eyes, that she was persuaded that this appearance had more than a little to do with the awful rider, the terrific storm, and myself who had heard the sound of the phantom-hoofs.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000197","text":"As he ascended the hill, she looked after him, with wide and pale but unshrinking eyes; then turning in, shut and locked the door behind her, as by a natural instinct.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000198","text":"After two or three of her significant nods, accompanied by the compression of her lips, she said:--","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000199","text":"“He need not think to take me in, wizard as he is, with his disguises.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000200","text":"Duncan, my dear, when you suspect anything, do not be too incredulous.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000201","text":"This human demon is of course a wizard still, and knows how to make himself, as well as anything he touches, take a quite different appearance from the real one; only every appearance must bear some resemblance, however distant, to the natural form.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000202","text":"That man you saw at the door was the phantom of which I have been telling you.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000203","text":"What he is after now, of course, I cannot tell; but you must keep a bold heart, and a firm and wary foot, as you go home to-night.”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:courage","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000204","text":"I showed some surprise, I do not doubt; and, perhaps, some fear as well; but I only said, “How do you know him, Margaret?”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000205","text":"“I can hardly tell you,” she replied; “but I do know him.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000206","text":"Often, of a wild night, when there is moonlight enough by fits, I see him tearing around this little valley, just on the top edge--all round; the lady’s hair and the horses mane and tail driving far behind, and mingling, vaporous, with the stormy clouds.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000207","text":"In this case I hear no sound, except now and then a clank from the broken shoe.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000208","text":"But I did not mean to tell you that I had ever seen him.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000209","text":"His power is limited; else ill enough would he work, the miscreant.”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000210","text":"“But,” said I, “what has all this, terrible as it is, to do with the fright you took at my telling you that I had heard the sound of the broken shoe? Surely you are not afraid of only a storm?”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000211","text":"But the fact is, that that sound is seldom heard, and never, as far as I know, by any of the blood of that wicked man, without betokening some ill to one of the family, and most probably to the one who hears it--but I am not quite sure about that.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:relationships","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000212","text":"Only some evil it does portend, although a long time may elapse before it shows itself; and I have a hope it may mean some one else than you.”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000213","text":"“I know no one better able to bear it than I am; and I hope, whatever it may be, that I only shall have to meet it.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000214","text":"It must surely be something serious to be so foretold--it can hardly be connected with my disappointment in being compelled to be a pedagogue instead of a soldier.”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000215","text":"“Do not trouble yourself about that, Duncan,” replied she.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000216","text":"The same day you told me of the clank of the broken horseshoe, I saw you return wounded from battle, and fall fainting from your horse in the street of a great city--only fainting, thank God.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000217","text":"But I have particular reasons for being uneasy at your hearing that boding sound.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000218","text":"Can you tell me the day and hour of your birth?”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000219","text":"“No,” I replied. “It seems very odd when I think of it, but I really do not know even the day.”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000220","text":"“Nor any one else; which is stranger still,” she answered.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000221","text":"“We were in terrible anxiety about your mother at the time.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mental-health","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000222","text":"So ill was she, after you were just born, in a strange, unaccountable way, that you lay almost neglected for more than an hour.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000223","text":"In the very act of giving birth to you, she seemed to the rest around her to be out of her mind, so wildly did she talk; but I knew better.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000224","text":"I knew that she was fighting some evil power; and what power it was, I knew full well; for twice, during her pains, I heard the click of the horseshoe.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000225","text":"After her delivery, she lay as if in a trance, neither dead, nor at rest, but as if frozen to ice, and conscious of it all the while.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000226","text":"Once more I heard the terrible sound of iron; and, at the moment, your mother started from her trance, screaming, ‘My child!","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000227","text":"my child!’ We suddenly became aware that no one had attended to the child, and rushed to the place where he lay wrapped in a blanket.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000228","text":"Uncovering him, we found him black in the face, and spotted with dark spots upon the throat.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000229","text":"I thought he was dead; but, with great and almost hopeless pains, we succeeded in making him breathe, and he gradually recovered.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:recovery","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000230","text":"But his mother continued dreadfully exhausted.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000231","text":"It seemed as if she had spent her life for her child’s defence and birth.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000232","text":"About a week after your birth, as near as I can guess, just in the gloaming, I heard yet again the awful clank--only once.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000233","text":"Your mother slept, and you lay asleep beside her.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000234","text":"A horror fell upon me suddenly, though I neither saw nor heard anything.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000235","text":"Your mother started from her sleep with a cry, which sounded as if it came from far away, out of a dream, and did not belong to this world.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000236","text":"She sat up in bed, with wide staring eyes and half-open rigid lips, and, feeble as she was, thrust her arms straight out before her with great force, her hands open and lifted up, with the palms outwards.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000237","text":"The whole action was of one violently repelling another.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000238","text":"She began to talk wildly as she had done before you were born, but, though I seemed to hear and understand it all at the time, I could not recall a word of it afterwards.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000239","text":"It was as if I had listened to it when half asleep.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000240","text":"I attempted to soothe her, putting my arms round her, but she seemed quite unconscious of my presence, and my arms seemed powerless upon the fixed muscles of hers.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000241","text":"Not that I tried to constrain her, for I knew that a battle was going on of some kind or other, and my interference might do awful mischief.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000242","text":"I only tried to comfort and encourage her.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:courage","theme:love","theme:resilience","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000243","text":"All the time, I was in a state of indescribable cold and suffering, whether more bodily or mental I could not tell.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000244","text":"But at length I heard yet again the clank of the shoe A sudden peace seemed to fall upon my mind--or was it a warm, odorous wind that filled the room?","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000245","text":"Your mother dropped her arms, and turned feebly towards her baby.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000246","text":"She smiled like a glorified spirit, and fell back exhausted on the pillow.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:animism","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000247","text":"I went to the other side of the room to get a cordial.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000248","text":"When I returned to the bedside, I saw at once that she was dead.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000249","text":"Her face smiled still, with an expression of the uttermost bliss.”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000250","text":"Nurse ceased, trembling as overcome by the recollection; and I was too much moved and awed to speak.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:love","theme:resilience","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000251","text":"At length, resuming the conversation, she said: “You see it is no wonder, Duncan, my dear, if, after all this, I should find, when I wanted to fix the date of your birth, that I could not determine the day or the hour when it took place.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000252","text":"But it was strange that no one else could, any more than I.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000253","text":"As I carried you across the room to lay you down, for I assisted at your birth, I happened to look up to the window.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000254","text":"Then I saw what I did not forget, although I did not think of it again till many days after,--a bright star was shining on the very tip of the thin crescent moon.”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000255","text":"“Oh, then,” said I, “it is possible to determine the day and the very hour when my birth took place.”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000256","text":"“See the good of book-learning!” replied she. “When you work it out, just let me know, my dear, that I may remember it.”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000257","text":"A silence of some moments followed. Margaret resumed:--","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:solitude","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000258","text":"If so, his persecution of you, and of your mother for your sake, is easy to understand.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000259","text":"And if so, you will never be able to rest till you find your fere, wherever she may have been born on the face of the earth.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000260","text":"For born she must be, long ere now, for you to find.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000261","text":"I misdoubt me much, however, if you will find her without great conflict and suffering between, for the Powers of Darkness will be against you; though I have good hope that you will overcome at last.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:resilience","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000262","text":"You must forgive the fancies of a foolish old woman, my dear.”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000263","text":"I will not try to describe the strange feelings, almost sensations, that arose in me while listening to these extraordinary utterances, lest it should be supposed I was ready to believe all that Margaret narrated or concluded.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000264","text":"I could not help doubting her sanity; but no more could I help feeling very peculiarly moved by her narrative.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000265","text":"I went out into the midst of the storm, into the alternating throbs of blackness and radiance; now the possessor of no more room than what my body filled, and now isolated in world-wide space. And the thunder seemed to follow me, bellowing after me as I went.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000266","text":"Absorbed in the story I had heard, I took my way, as I thought, homewards.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000267","text":"I should have said, before that night, that I could have gone home blindfold.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000268","text":"Whether the lightning bewildered me and made me take a false turn, I cannot tell; for the hardest thing to understand, in intellectual as well as moral mistakes, is--how we came to go wrong.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000269","text":"But after wandering for some time, plunged in meditation, and with no warning whatever of the presence of inimical powers, a brilliant lightning-flash showed me that at least I was not near home.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000270","text":"The light was prolonged for a second or two by a slight electric pulsation; and by that I distinguished a wide space of blackness on the ground in front of me.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000271","text":"Once more wrapped in the folds of a thick darkness, I dared not move.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:courage","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000272","text":"Suddenly it occurred to me what the blackness was, and whither I had wandered.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000273","text":"It was a huge quarry, of great depth, long disused, and half filled with water.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000274","text":"A few more steps would have carried me over the brink.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000275","text":"I stood still, waiting for the next flash, that I might be quite sure of the way I was about to take before I ventured to move.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000276","text":"While I stood, I fancied I heard a single hollow plunge in the black water far below.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000277","text":"When the lightning came, I turned, and took my path in another direction.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000278","text":"After walking for some time across the heath, I fell. The fall became a roll, and down a steep declivity I went, over and over, arriving at the bottom uninjured.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000279","text":"Another flash soon showed me where I was-in the hollow valley, within a couple of hundred yards from nurse’s cottage.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000280","text":"There was no light in it, except the feeblest glow from the embers of her peat fire.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000281","text":"“She is in bed,” I said to myself, “and I will not disturb her.” Yet something drew me towards the little window.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000282","text":"At length, as I kept gazing, I saw something, indistinct in the darkness, like an outstretched human form.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000283","text":"The moon had been up for some time, but had been quite concealed by tempestuous clouds.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000284","text":"A stranger to her habits would have thought she was dead; but she had so much of the appearance she had had on a former occasion, that I concluded at once she was in one of her trances.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000285","text":"But having often heard that persons in such a condition ought not to be disturbed, and feeling quite sure she knew best how to manage herself, I turned, though reluctantly, and left the lone cottage behind me in the night, with the death-like woman lying motionless in the midst of it.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mortality","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000286","text":"I found my way home without any further difficulty, and went to bed, where I soon fell asleep, thoroughly wearied, more by the mental excitement I had been experiencing than by the amount of bodily exercise I had gone through.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000287","text":"My sleep was tormented with awful dreams; yet, strange to say, I awoke in the morning refreshed and fearless.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:courage","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000288","text":"The sun was shining through the chinks in my shutters, which had been closed because of the storm, and was making streaks and bands of golden brilliancy upon the wall.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000289","text":"I had dressed and completed my preparations long before I heard the steps of the servant who came to call me.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000290","text":"The time of the ghostly moonshine passes by, and the great positive sunlight comes.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000291","text":"A man who dreams, and knows that he is dreaming, thinks he knows what waking is; but knows it so little, that he mistakes, one after another, many a vague and dim change in his dream for an awaking.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000292","text":"When the true waking comes at last, he is filled and overflowed with the power of its reality.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000293","text":"He feels as if the darkness were cast to an infinite distance behind him.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000294","text":"So shall it be with us when we wake from this dream of life into the truer life beyond, and find all our present notions of being, thrown back as into a dim, vapoury region of dreamland, where yet we thought we knew, and whence we looked forward into the present.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000295","text":"This must be what Novalis means when he says: “Our life is not a dream; but it may become a dream, and perhaps ought to become one.”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000296","text":"And so I looked back upon the strange history of my past; sometimes asking myself,--“Can it be that all this realty happened to the same _me_, who am now thinking about it in doubt and wonder?”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:beauty","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000297","text":"As my father accompanied me to the door, where the gig, which was to carry me over the first stage of my journey, was in waiting, a large target of hide, well studded with brass nails, which had hung in the hall for time unknown--to me, at least--fell on the floor with a dull bang.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000298","text":"My father started, but said nothing; and, as it seemed to me, rather pressed my departure than otherwise.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000299","text":"I would have replaced the old piece of armour before I went, but he would not allow me to touch it, saying, with a grim smile,--","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000300","text":"“Take that for an omen, my boy, that your armour must be worn over the conscience, and not over the body. Be a man, Duncan, my boy. Fear nothing, and do your duty.”","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000301","text":"A grasp of the hand was all the good-bye I could make; and I was soon rattling away to meet the coach _for Edinburgh and London.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000302","text":"Seated on the top, I_ was soon buried in a reverie, from which I was suddenly startled by the sound of tinkling iron.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000303","text":"Could it be that my adversary was riding unseen alongside of the coach?","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000304","text":"But I soon discovered the cause of the sound, and laughed at my own apprehensiveness.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000305","text":"For I observed that the sound was repeated every time that we passed any trees by the wayside, and that it was the peculiar echo they gave of the loose chain and steel work about the harness.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000306","text":"The sound was quite different from that thrown back by the houses on the road.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000307","text":"I became perfectly familiar with it before the day was over.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000308","text":"I reached London in safety, and slept at the house of an old friend of my father, who treated me with great kindness, and seemed altogether to take a liking to me. Before I left he held out a hope of being able, some day or other, to procure for me what I so much desired--a commission in the army.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000309","text":"After spending a day or two with him, and seeing something of London, I climbed once more on the roof of a coach; and, late in the afternoon, was set down at the great gate of Hilton Hall.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000310","text":"I walked up the broad avenue, through the final arch of which, as through a huge Gothic window, I saw the hall in the distance.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000311","text":"Everything about me looked strange, rich, and lovely.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000312","text":"Accustomed to the scanty flowers and diminutive wood of my own country, what I now saw gave me a feeling of majestic plenty, which I can recall at will, but which I have never experienced again.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000313","text":"Behind the trees which formed the avenue, I saw a shrubbery, composed entirely of flowering plants, almost all unknown to me.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000314","text":"Issuing from the avenue, I found myself amid open, wide, lawny spaces, in which the flower-beds lay like islands of colour.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000315","text":"A statue on a pedestal, the only white thing in the surrounding green, caught my eye.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000316","text":"I had seen scarcely any sculpture; and this, attracting my attention by a favourite contrast of colour, retained it by its own beauty.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:beauty","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000317","text":"It was a Dryad, or some nymph of the woods, who had just glided from the solitude of the trees behind, and had sprung upon the pedestal to look wonderingly around her.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000318","text":"A few large brown leaves lay at her feet, borne thither by some eddying wind from the trees behind.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000319","text":"As I gazed, filled with a new pleasure, a drop of rain upon my face made me look up.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000320","text":"From a grey, fleecy cloud, with sun-whitened border, a light, gracious, plentiful rain was falling.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000321","text":"A rainbow sprang across the sky, and the statue stood within the rainbow.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:solitude","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000322","text":"I followed in the direction of the mansion, which was large, and of several styles and ages.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000323","text":"It was neglected and out of repair, and had in consequence a desolate, almost sepulchral look, an expression heightened by the number of large cypresses which grew along its line.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000324","text":"I went up to the central door and knocked.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000325","text":"It was opened by a grave, elderly butler.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000326","text":"I passed under its flat arch, as if into the midst of the waiting events of my story.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000327","text":"For, as I glanced around the hall, my consciousness was suddenly saturated, if I may be allowed the expression, with the strange feeling--known to everyone, and yet so strange--that I had seen it before; that, in fact, I knew it perfectly.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000328","text":"This sensation, in every case, died away at once, leaving that portion such as it might be expected to look to one who had never before entered the place.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000329","text":"I was received by the housekeeper, a little, prim, benevolent old lady, with colourless face and antique head-dress, who led me to the room prepared for me.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000330","text":"My bedroom was a few paces down a passage to the right.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000331","text":"Left alone, I proceeded to make a more critical survey of my room.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000332","text":"Its look of ancient mystery was to me incomparably more attractive than any show of elegance or comfort could have been.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000333","text":"It was large and low, panelled throughout in oak, black with age, and worm-eaten in many parts--otherwise entire.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000334","text":"Both the windows looked into the little court or yard before mentioned.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000335","text":"All the heavier furniture of the room was likewise of black oak, but the chairs and couches were covered with faded tapestry and tarnished gilding, apparently the superannuated members of the general household of seats.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000336","text":"I could give an individual description of each, for every atom in that room, large enough for discernable shape or colour, seems branded into my brain.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000337","text":"If I happen to have the least feverishness on me, the moment I fall asleep, I am in that room.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000338","text":"When the bell rang for dinner, I managed to find my way to the drawing-room, where were assembled Lady Hilton, her only daughter, a girl of about thirteen, and the two boys, my pupils.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000339","text":"Lady Hilton would have been pleasant, could she have been as natural as she wished to appear.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000340","text":"She received me with some degree of kindness; but the half-cordiality of her manner towards me was evidently founded on the impassableness of the gulf between us.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000341","text":"I knew at once that we should never be friends; that she would never come down from the lofty table-land upon which she walked; and that if, after being years in the house, I should happen to be dying, she would send the housekeeper to me.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000342","text":"All right, no doubt; I only say that it was so.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000343","text":"She introduced to me my pupils; fine, open-eyed, manly English boys, with something a little overbearing in their manner, which speedily disappeared in relation to me.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000344","text":"Lady Hilton led the way to the dining-room; the elder boy gave his arm to his sister, and I was about to follow with the younger, when from one of the deep bay windows glided out, still in white, the same figure which had passed me upon the lawn.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000345","text":"With a slight bow, she preceded me, and followed the others down the great staircase.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000346","text":"Seated at table, I had leisure to make my observations upon them all; but most of my glances found their way to the lady who, twice that day, had affected me like an apparition.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000347","text":"What is time, but the airy ocean in which ghosts come and go!","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000348","text":"She was about twenty years of age; rather above the middle height, and rather slight in form; her complexion white rather than pale, her face being only less white than the deep marbly whiteness of her arms.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000349","text":"Her eyes were large, and full of liquid night--a night throbbing with the light of invisible stars.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000350","text":"Her hair seemed raven-black, and in quantity profuse.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000351","text":"The expression of her face, however, generally partook more of vagueness than any other characteristic.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000352","text":"Lady Hilton called her Lady Alice; and she never addressed Lady Hilton but in the same ceremonious style.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000353","text":"I afterwards learned from the old house-keeper, that Lady Alice’s position in the family was a very peculiar one.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:relationships","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000354","text":"Distantly connected with Lord Hilton’s family on the mother’s side, she was the daughter of the late Lord Glendarroch, and step-daughter to Lady Hilton, who had become Lady Hilton within a year after Lord Glendarroch’s death.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mortality","theme:relationships","theme:solitude","tradition:christianity","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000355","text":"Lady Alice, then quite a child, had accompanied her stepmother, to whom she was moderately attached, and who had been allowed to retain undisputed possession of her.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000356","text":"She had no near relatives, else the fortune I afterwards found to be at her disposal would have aroused contending claims to the right of guardianship.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000357","text":"Although she was in many respects kindly treated by her stepmother, certain peculiarities tended to her isolation from the family pursuits and pleasures.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:relationships","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000358","text":"She could neither spell her own language, nor even read it aloud.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000359","text":"Yet she delighted in reading to herself, though, for the most part, books which Mrs.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000360","text":"Her voice, when she spoke, had a quite indescribable music in it; yet she neither sang nor played.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000361","text":"Her habitual motion was more like a rhythmical gliding than an ordinary walk, yet she could not dance.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000362","text":"Not the less, however, I speculated on the subject.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000363","text":"One thing soon became evident to me: that she was considered not merely deficient as to the power of intellectual acquirement, but in a quite abnormal intellectual condition.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000364","text":"Of this, however, I could myself see no sign.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000365","text":"The peculiarity, almost oddity, of some of her remarks, was evidently not only misunderstood, but, with relation to her mental state, misinterpreted.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000366","text":"Such remarks Lady Hilton generally answered only by an elongation of the lips intended to represent a smile.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000367","text":"To me, they appeared to indicate a nature closely allied to genius, if not identical with it-a power of regarding things from an original point of view, which perhaps was the more unfettered in its operation from the fact that she was incapable of looking at them in the ordinary common-place way.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000368","text":"I am compelled to acknowledge, however, that with such utterances as these mingled now and then others, silly enough for any drawing-room young lady; which seemed again to be accepted by the family as proofs that she was not _altogether_ out of her right mind.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:relationships","theme:wisdom","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000369","text":"She was gentle and kind to the children, as they were still called; and they seemed reasonably fond of her.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000370","text":"There was something to me exceedingly touching in the solitariness of this girl; for no one spoke to her as if she were like other people, or as if any heartiness were possible between them.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000371","text":"Perhaps no one could have felt quite at home with her but a mother, whose heart had been one with hers from a season long anterior to the development of any repulsive oddity.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000372","text":"But her position was one of peculiar isolation, for no one really approached her individual being; and that she should be unaware of this loneliness, seemed to me saddest of all.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000373","text":"I soon found, however, that the most distant attempt on my part to show her attention, was either received with absolute indifference, or coldly repelled without the slightest acknowledgment.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000374","text":"But I return to the first night of my sojourn at Hilton Hall.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000375","text":"Strange was its look as I entered--as of a room hollowed out of the past, for a memorial of dead times.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000376","text":"The fire had sunk low, and lay smouldering beneath the white ashes, like the life of the world beneath the snow, or the heart of a man beneath cold and grey thoughts.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000377","text":"I lighted the candles which stood upon the table, but the room, instead of being brightened looked blacker than before, for the light revealed its essential blackness.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000378","text":"As I cast my eyes around me, standing with my back to the hearth (on which, for mere companionship’s sake, I had just heaped fresh wood), a thrill ran suddenly throughout my frame.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000379","text":"I felt as if, did it last a moment longer, I should become aware of another presence in the room; but, happily for me, it ceased before it had reached that point; and I, recovering my courage, remained ignorant of the cause of my fear, if there were any, other than the nature of the room itself.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:recovery","language:en","theme:courage","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:nature","theme:resilience","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000380","text":"With a candle in my hand, I proceeded to open the various cupboards and closets.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000381","text":"At first I found nothing remarkable about any of them.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000382","text":"The latter were quite empty, except the last I came to, which had a piece of very old elaborate tapestry hanging at the back of it.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000383","text":"Lifting this up, I saw what seemed at first to be panels, corresponding to those which formed the room; but on looking more closely, I discovered that this back of the closet was, or had been, a door.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000384","text":"There was nothing unusual in this, especially in such an old house; but the discovery roused in me a strong desire to know what lay behind the old door.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000385","text":"I found that it was secured only by an ordinary bolt, from which the handle had been removed.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000386","text":"Soothing my conscience with the reflection that I had a right to know what sort of place had communication with my room, I succeeded, by the help of my deer-knife, in forcing back the rusty bolt; and though, from the stiffness of the hinges, I dreaded a crack, they yielded at last with only a creak.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000387","text":"The opening door revealed a large hall, empty utterly, save of dust and cobwebs, which festooned it in all quarters, and gave it an appearance of unutterable desolation.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000388","text":"The now familiar feeling, that I had seen the place before, filled my mind the first moment, and passed away the next.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000389","text":"A broad, right-angled staircase, with massive banisters, rose from the middle of the hall.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000390","text":"This staircase could not have originally belonged to the ancient wing which I had observed on my first approach, being much more modern; but I was convinced, from the observations I had made as to the situation of my room, that I was bordering upon, if not within, the oldest portion of the pile.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000391","text":"In spite of novelty, antiquity, speculation, and dread, I was soon fast asleep; becoming thereby a fitter inhabitant of such regions, than when I moved about with restless and disturbing curiosity, through their ancient and death-like repose.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mortality","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000392","text":"I made no use of my discovered door, although I always intended doing so; especially after, in talking about the building with Lady Hilton, I found that I was at perfect liberty to make what excursions I pleased into the deserted portions.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000393","text":"My pupils turned out to be teachable, and therefore my occupation was pleasant. Their sister frequently came to me for help, as there happened to be just then an interregnum of governesses: soon she settled into a regular pupil.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000394","text":"Though my room was so far from the great hall, I heard the clank of his spurs on its pavement.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000395","text":"I trembled; for it sounded like the broken shoe.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000396","text":"But I shook off the influence in a moment, heartily ashamed of its power over me.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000397","text":"Soon I became familiar enough both with the sound and its cause; for his lordship rarely went anywhere except on horseback, and was booted and spurred from morning till night.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000398","text":"He received me with some appearance of interest, which immediately stiffened and froze. Beginning to shake hands with me as if he meant it, he instantly dropped my hand, as if it had stung him.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000399","text":"His nobility was of that sort which stands in constant need of repair.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000400","text":"Like a weakly constitution, it required keeping up, and his lordship could not be said to neglect it; for he seemed to find his principal employment in administering continuous doses of obsequiousness to his own pride.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000401","text":"His rank, like a coat made for some large ancestor, hung loose upon him: he was always trying to persuade himself that it was an excellent fit, but ever with an unacknowledged misgiving.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000402","text":"This misgiving might have done him good, had he not met it with renewed efforts at looking that which he feared he was not.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000403","text":"Yet this man was capable of the utmost persistency in carrying out any scheme he had once devised.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:resilience","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000404","text":"Enough of him for the present: I seldom came into contact with him.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000405","text":"I scarcely ever saw Lady Alice, except at dinner, or by accidental meeting in the grounds and passages of the house; and then she took no notice of me whatever.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000406","text":"One day, a week after his arrival, Lord Hilton gave a dinner-party to some of his neighbours and tenants.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:christianity","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000407","text":"I entered the drawing-room rather late, and saw that, though there were many guests, not one was talking to Lady Alice.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000408","text":"She appeared, however, altogether unconscious of neglect.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000409","text":"Presently dinner was announced, and the company marshalled themselves, and took their way to the dining-room.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:solitude","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000410","text":"Lady Alice was left unattended, the guests taking their cue from the behaviour of their entertainers.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000411","text":"I ventured to go up to her, and offer her my arm.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000412","text":"She made me a haughty bow, and passed on before me unaccompanied.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000413","text":"I could not help feeling hurt at this, and I think she saw it; but it made no difference to her behaviour, except that she avoided everything that might occasion me the chance of offering my services.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000414","text":"Nor did I get any further with Lady Hilton.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000415","text":"Her manner and smile remained precisely the same as on our first interview.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000416","text":"She did not even show any interest in the fact that her daughter, Lady Lucy, had joined her brothers in the schoolroom.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"attar-ext-000417","text":"I had an uncomfortable feeling that the latter was like her mother, and was not to be trusted.","author":"Attar","source":"Conference of the Birds — FitzGerald","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:relationships","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."}]}